=========================================
C++ LIST (Doubly Linked List)
INTERVIEW PREPARATION NOTES
=========================================

1. What is list?
----------------

std::list is a doubly linked list provided by STL.

Each node contains:

[data][prev][next]

Example:

list<int> l;

l.push_back(10);
l.push_back(20);
l.push_back(30);

Result:

10 <-> 20 <-> 30

-----------------------------------------

2. Internal Implementation
--------------------------

Implemented as a Doubly Linked List.

Node Structure:

+------+-------+------+
| prev | data  | next |
+------+-------+------+

Example:

NULL <- 10 <-> 20 <-> 30 -> NULL

Each node stores:

1. Data
2. Pointer to previous node
3. Pointer to next node

Interview Q:
How is list implemented internally?

Answer:
std::list is implemented as a doubly linked list where each node stores data along with pointers to the previous and next nodes.

-----------------------------------------

3. Why Use list?
----------------

Vector Problem:

Insert in middle:

[10][20][30][40]

Insert 25:

[10][20][25][30][40]

Elements must shift.

Cost = O(n)

List:

10 <-> 20 <-> 30 <-> 40

Insert 25:

10 <-> 20 <-> 25 <-> 30 <-> 40

Only pointers change.

Cost = O(1) after reaching position.

-----------------------------------------

4. Complexity
-------------

Access by index        O(n)

push_front()          O(1)
push_back()           O(1)

pop_front()           O(1)
pop_back()            O(1)

insert(iterator)      O(1)
erase(iterator)       O(1)

find()                O(n)

size()                O(1)

-----------------------------------------

5. Random Access?
-----------------

list does NOT support:

l[5]

Not allowed.

Reason:

Nodes are not contiguous.

Need traversal.

Complexity:

O(n)

Interview Q:
Why does list not support random access?

Answer:
Because elements are stored as linked nodes rather than contiguous memory, so the container must traverse nodes sequentially.

-----------------------------------------

6. Contiguous Memory?
---------------------

vector:
✓ Contiguous

deque:
✗ Non-contiguous blocks

list:
✗ Completely non-contiguous

Example:

Node1 -> Address 1000
Node2 -> Address 9000
Node3 -> Address 4000

Interview Q:
Does list store elements contiguously?

Answer:
No.

-----------------------------------------

7. Iterator Stability
---------------------

Major Advantage.

Insert:

l.insert(it, 100);

Existing iterators remain valid.

Erase:

Only iterator pointing to erased node becomes invalid.

Interview Q:
Why are list iterators more stable than vector iterators?

Answer:
Because nodes are linked together and insertion/removal only changes pointers without moving existing elements.

-----------------------------------------

8. Why Insert/Delete O(1)?
--------------------------

Given iterator:

it --> 20

Insert 15:

10 <-> 15 <-> 20 <-> 30

Only pointer updates.

No shifting.

Complexity:

O(1)

Important:

Finding position first may take O(n).

Interview Answer:

Insertion/deletion is O(1) only when the iterator to the position is already available.

-----------------------------------------

9. list vs vector
-----------------

vector
------
Contiguous memory
Random access O(1)
Insert middle O(n)
Better cache locality

list
----
Doubly linked list
No random access
Insert middle O(1)
Poor cache locality

Interview Q:
Why is vector usually preferred over list?

Answer:
Modern CPUs benefit from cache locality. Although list provides O(1) insertion/deletion, vector is often faster in practice because its elements are stored contiguously.

-----------------------------------------

