14. Iterator Invalidation
-------------------------

Insert:
-------
l.insert(it, 100);

All existing iterators remain valid.

Erase:
------
Only iterator pointing to the erased node becomes invalid.

Example:

auto it = l.begin();

l.erase(it);

it becomes invalid.

Other iterators remain valid.

Interview Q:
Which iterators become invalid after erase()?

Answer:
Only iterators/references to the erased element become invalid.

15. splice()
------------

One of the most powerful list functions.

Moves elements from one list to another
without copying or moving elements.

Example:

list<int> l1 = {1,2,3};
list<int> l2 = {4,5,6};

l1.splice(l1.end(), l2);

Result:

l1 = {1,2,3,4,5,6}
l2 = {}

Complexity:

O(1)

Interview Q:
Why is splice() efficient?

Answer:
Because it only relinks pointers and does not copy elements.

16. list vs forward_list
------------------------

list
----
Doubly linked list

[data][prev][next]

Can traverse:
Forward and Backward

Supports:
push_back()
push_front()

More memory usage

forward_list
------------
Singly linked list

[data][next]

Can traverse:
Forward only

Supports:
push_front()

Less memory usage

Interview Q:
Difference between list and forward_list?

Answer:
list is a doubly linked list with bidirectional traversal, while forward_list is a singly linked list with lower memory overhead.

Why is vector usually preferred over list even though list has O(1) insertion/deletion?
Although list provides O(1) insertion and deletion, it suffers from poor cache locality because nodes are scattered in memory. 
Vector stores elements contiguously, making traversal 
much faster due to better CPU cache utilization. Therefore vector is usually faster in real-world applications.
